Title: Social Preferences and Fairness Norms as Informal Institutions: Experimental Evidence 
Abstract:
 We conduct a series of dictator games in which the status of the dictator
 relative to other players varies across treatments. Experiments are
 conducted in a conventional university lab and in villages in rural Kenya.
 We find that status is an important determinant of dictator game giving,
 but the relative importance of earned and unearned status differs across
 cultures.
