Author-Name: Torberg Falch  
Title: Teacher Mobility Responses to Wage Changes: Evidence from a Quasi-natural Experiment 
Abstract:
 This paper utilizes a Norwegian experiment with exogenous wage changes to
 study teachers' turnover decisions. Within a completely centralized wage
 setting system, teachers in schools with a high degree of teacher
 vacancies in the past got a wage premium of about 10 percent during the
 period 1993-94 to 2002-03. The empirical strategy exploits that several
 schools switched status during the empirical period. In a fixed effects
 framework, I find that the wage premium reduces the probability of
 voluntary quits by six percentage points, which implies a short run labor
 supply elasticity of about 1 1/4 .
