Title: Optimal Proof Burdens, Deterrence, and the Chilling of Desirable Behavior 
Abstract:
 The optimal stringency of the burden of proof is characterized in a model
 in which relaxing the proof burden enhances deterrence but also chills
 desirable behavior. The result are strikingly different from those in
 prior work that uses a simpler model in which individuals only choose
 whether to commit a harmful act (so only deterrence is at stake).
 Moreover, the qualitative differences between the optimal rule and the
 familiar preponderance of the evidence rule--and related rules that look
 to Bayesian posteriors--are great, much more so than revealed by prior
 work.
