Author-Name: Howard F. Chang  
Title: The Effect of Allowing Pollution Offsets with Imperfect Enforcement 
Abstract:
 Public policies for pollution control, including climate change policies,
 sometimes allow polluters in one sector subject to an emissions cap to
 offset excessive emissions with pollution abatement in another sector. The
 government may find it more costly to verify offset claims than to verify
 compliance with emissions caps. Concerns about such enforcement
 difficulties may lead regulators to restrict the use of offsets. We
 demonstrate that allowing offsets may increase pollution abatement and
 reduce illegal pollution, even if the government has a fixed enforcement
 budget. We explore circumstances that may make allowing pollution offsets
 an attractive option when enforcement is costly.
