Title: Do Residential Customers Respond to Hourly Prices? Evidence from a Dynamic Pricing Experiment 
Abstract:
 This paper uses the results of a dynamic pricing experiment for households
 in the District of Columbia to determine whether the reduction in demand
 associated with an hourly price signal is economically different from the
 demand reduction associated with an equivalent price signal that is four
 times longer in duration. For both regular and all-electric customers, the
 percentage demand reduction associated with a given percentage increase in
 the hourly price is approximately equal to the percentage demand reduction
 associated with the same percentage price increase of a much longer
 duration.
