Author-Name: Matthew C. Weinberg  
Title: More Evidence on the Performance of Merger Simulations 
Abstract:
 Merger simulations are commonly used to simulate the effects of potential
 mergers. Despite the large resources devoted to merger review, little
 evidence exists on the accuracy of these methods. This paper uses the
 acquisition of Tambrands by Proctor and Gamble to provide evidence on the
 efficacy of merger simulation. Two simple demand systems are estimated
 under several identification assumptions and combined with a static model
 of price competition. Simulations predict small price effects of about 1
 percent for the merging firms' brands, while direct estimates indicate the
 merger raised prices by 5-8 percent.
